I wonder if this is part of a larger cultural movement that’s about to form. For a while I’ve felt like as a culture we’ll become more and more digitally saturated until we hit a breaking point that causes a reactive movement to pull away from digital overconsumption. A “Digital Bulimia”. Taking in and taking in but never really digesting what we read or applying it to our lives.
I believe there will be a place for quality print subscriptions and models that focus on taking it slow and digesting what you read. Step away from the fire hydrant to get a glass of water. I’ve recently enjoyed a subscription to offscreenmag.com.
We will see more quality digital reads that encourage a dedicated slow paced consumption.

Sometimes I wonder if I am the only one who thinks this way. I happen to live in an area where design companies only care about the money and use cheap templates to produce low quality sites but then charge high prices.
After reading this article I feel like I have to do my part in this crazy web design world and start my own business. I know it will be tough at first but if I’m lucky I might be able to start a new renaissance in my area. If these people can do this then maybe I can too.

Nice to see this trend of substance over soundbite. We should all do our part to step back and engage in thoughtful consideration and understanding, and to resist the idea that we’re always missing something somewhere. Not easy in today’s culture, but over time it can become a learned habit.

Really inspiring read. I too think we should learn to sift our work and the projects we take on to build better products. In my own daily life, the ‘information overload’ makes this very difficult. I think I’ll take a step back and I hope to see more designers and writers moving in this direction.
This article is spot on and a great read! Most of the net now a days is full of quickly written and poorly thought material, creating cheap designs for that quick buck. Its truly a shame.
